critters.name: Bheemeshwara Gupchup
critters.story: Bheemeshwara Gupchup, a mischievous cloud-dwelling rakshasa (demon) of moderate size, wasn't always a fluffy resident of the heavens.  He was once a notorious street vendor in Varanasi, famous (or infamous) for his incredibly spicy *gupchup* (pani puri).  His gupchup were so fiery they could melt granite, and his customers, though addicted, often complained.  One day, angered by a particularly scathing review from a food critic (a grumpy yaksha named Kumbhakarna), Bheemeshwara swore revenge—a truly epic, fiery revenge!  He proceeded to unleash a super-spicy gupchup cloud that engulfed the city.  The gods, witnessing this culinary catastrophe, intervened.  They found Bheemeshwara's fiery spirit amusing, but his culinary skills concerning.  To prevent further chaos, they turned him into a cloud-shaped version of himself, eternally drifting above the earth, a testament to the explosive power of excessive spice. Now, every so often, rain from Bheemeshwara Gupchup's cloud has a subtle hint of chilli, which is said to bring good luck (or serious heartburn).

critters.name: Meghdoot  Mackerel
critters.story: Meghdoot Mackerel wasn't your average fish.  He was a mischievous, perpetually-hungry creature from the mythical River Saraswati, known for his uncanny ability to shapeshift (mostly into increasingly ridiculous things to avoid getting caught by the river's resident hungry crocodiles).  One day, during a particularly ambitious attempt to transform into a fearsome Gargoyle, he accidentally inhaled a potent gust of wind imbued with the magic of Indra’s thunderbolt. This caused him to be blasted high into the heavens, his body permanently altered into a cloud-fish form, forever soaring through the sky in a state of bewildered flight. He still occasionally attempts to shapeshift, but now all he manages are bizarre cloud formations. The crocodiles are reportedly relieved.
